<br>
-don't go for something too complicated (art wise) or it may never get off the ground.<br>
<br>
-do &quot;buffer pages&quot; before you start, so you're always an episode or two ahead.<br>
<br>
-budget your time &amp; don't leave pages to the last minute, consistant updates are important.<br>
<br>
-don't go for something too complicated (story wise) or it may just become too daunting. Try and break a big story up into self contained episodes.<br>
<br>
-be comitted &amp; be prepared for nobody to like it. The stories on the web with big fanbases have <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>grown</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to that level.<br>
<br>
-have a good website. Slick pages make a lot of difference, and people on the net have notoriously short attention...ohh look a bird!<br>
<br>
-plan your website for the lowest common denominator. ie: someone with a slow modem and no flash.<br>
<br>
-Characters are <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>vital</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->. Your readers must sympathise with them or they won't keep coming back.<br>
<br>
-cliffhangers are important too, even if they're just minor or a little joke at the end of the page. read TinTin, as that does this excellently, and was originally published one page a week.<br>
<br>
